// Vitest Snapshot v1, https://vitest.dev/guide/snapshot.html

exports[`StepExplainer tier snapshots > matches copy structure snapshot for business tier 1`] = `"<article data-testid="wizard-step-explainer"><aside data-testid="wizard-explainer-enterprise-note" style="margin-bottom:12px;padding:10px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(79,70,229,0.12);border:1px solid rgba(99,102,241,0.35);color:#c7d2fe;font-size:12px">You are on the Business/Enterprise plan. The off-band validation pod is included in your plan.</aside><header style="margin-bottom:12px"><h2 style="margin:0;font-size:16px">Off-band validation for high-assurance environments</h2></header><div style="max-height:min(48vh, 420px);overflow-y:auto;margin-bottom:16px;padding-right:4px" role="region" aria-label="Off-band validation explainer" data-testid="wizard-explainer-scroll"><section style="margin-bottom:16px"><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">BEAP is designed to validate messages safely by default. In standard mode, depackaging and validation run on this computer inside an isolated local container with fail-closed behavior and strict validation controls.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">This setup adds another layer for higher-risk environments: it deploys a small validation pod—built from the same code that runs on this computer—onto a Linux VPS you control. A small VPS with root access is enough.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">In high-assurance mode, email depackaging happens through the Edge Ingestor. The VPS receives the email content first, depackages it, validates it, and issues a cryptographic validation certificate. Only certified, validated content is then delivered to this computer.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Native BEAP capsules can still be received directly, depending on your security settings. For routes configured to require Edge Ingestor, the local app accepts only capsules with a valid Edge certificate. For routes that allow direct native BEAP, local container validation still runs normally.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">High-assurance mode reduces endpoint exposure further. Malformed attachments, zip bombs, complex MIME structures, and high-volume invalid traffic are handled by the VPS before they reach this machine.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Your computer still performs full local validation as a second check. The Edge certificate is a gate, not a replacement. If the certificate is missing where required, invalid, or local validation fails, the message is rejected.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">The Edge Ingestor also signs the validated content and its hashes. Any tampering between the VPS and this computer invalidates the certificate.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Local AI analysis remains available to assess phishing, scam, and social-engineering risks before the user interacts with the message. In high-assurance mode, links and attachments should not be opened inside the host environment. Paid tiers can clone the message to a connected sandbox orchestrator, where links and attachments are opened off-band instead of on this computer.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">This mode is intended for users and organizations with higher assurance requirements. It does not mean standard BEAP validation is insecure; it adds an additional off-band isolation layer for cases where the stakes are higher.</p></section></div><footer data-testid="wizard-explainer-cta"><button type="button" style="padding:8px 14px;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #6366f1;background:#4f46e5;color:#fff;cursor:pointer;font-size:13px;font-weight:600" data-testid="wizard-explainer-continue">Continue to deployment</button></footer></article>"`;

exports[`StepExplainer tier snapshots > matches copy structure snapshot for free tier 1`] = `"<article data-testid="wizard-step-explainer"><header style="margin-bottom:12px"><h2 style="margin:0;font-size:16px">Off-band validation for high-assurance environments</h2></header><div style="max-height:min(48vh, 420px);overflow-y:auto;margin-bottom:16px;padding-right:4px" role="region" aria-label="Off-band validation explainer" data-testid="wizard-explainer-scroll"><section style="margin-bottom:16px"><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">BEAP is designed to validate messages safely by default. In standard mode, depackaging and validation run on this computer inside an isolated local container with fail-closed behavior and strict validation controls.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">This setup adds another layer for higher-risk environments: it deploys a small validation pod—built from the same code that runs on this computer—onto a Linux VPS you control. A small VPS with root access is enough.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">In high-assurance mode, email depackaging happens through the Edge Ingestor. The VPS receives the email content first, depackages it, validates it, and issues a cryptographic validation certificate. Only certified, validated content is then delivered to this computer.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Native BEAP capsules can still be received directly, depending on your security settings. For routes configured to require Edge Ingestor, the local app accepts only capsules with a valid Edge certificate. For routes that allow direct native BEAP, local container validation still runs normally.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">High-assurance mode reduces endpoint exposure further. Malformed attachments, zip bombs, complex MIME structures, and high-volume invalid traffic are handled by the VPS before they reach this machine.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Your computer still performs full local validation as a second check. The Edge certificate is a gate, not a replacement. If the certificate is missing where required, invalid, or local validation fails, the message is rejected.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">The Edge Ingestor also signs the validated content and its hashes. Any tampering between the VPS and this computer invalidates the certificate.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Local AI analysis remains available to assess phishing, scam, and social-engineering risks before the user interacts with the message. In high-assurance mode, links and attachments should not be opened inside the host environment. Paid tiers can clone the message to a connected sandbox orchestrator, where links and attachments are opened off-band instead of on this computer.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">This mode is intended for users and organizations with higher assurance requirements. It does not mean standard BEAP validation is insecure; it adds an additional off-band isolation layer for cases where the stakes are higher.</p></section></div><footer data-testid="wizard-explainer-cta"><button type="button" style="padding:8px 14px;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #6366f1;background:#4f46e5;color:#fff;cursor:pointer;font-size:13px;font-weight:600" data-testid="wizard-explainer-upgrade">Upgrade Now</button><div data-testid="tier-badge-with-refresh" role="group" aria-label="Current plan tier" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;margin-top:12px;position:relative"><style>@keyframes tier-badge-refresh-spin { from { transform: rotate(0deg); } to { transform: rotate(360deg); } }</style><span data-testid="tier-badge" style="padding:2px 8px;border-radius:4px;font-size:10px;font-weight:600;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.5px;background:rgba(99, 102, 241, 0.12);color:#a5b4fc;border:1px solid rgba(99, 102, 241, 0.2);line-height:1.4">Free</span><button type="button" data-testid="tier-badge-refresh" aria-label="Refresh plan tier to check upgrade" aria-busy="false" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;width:22px;height:22px;padding:0;border-radius:4px;border:1px solid transparent;background:transparent;color:#94a3b8;cursor:pointer;flex-shrink:0"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 1 1-2.64-6.36"></path><polyline points="21 3 21 9 15 9"></polyline></svg></button></div><p data-testid="wizard-explainer-upgrade-hint" style="margin:10px 0 0;font-size:12px;color:#94a3b8">Already upgraded? Click the refresh icon to re-check your plan.</p><a href="https://wrdesk.com/?page_id=1080&amp;v=5f02f0889301" style="display:none" aria-hidden="true">https://wrdesk.com/?page_id=1080&amp;v=5f02f0889301</a></footer></article>"`;

exports[`StepExplainer tier snapshots > matches copy structure snapshot for pro tier 1`] = `"<article data-testid="wizard-step-explainer"><header style="margin-bottom:12px"><h2 style="margin:0;font-size:16px">Off-band validation for high-assurance environments</h2></header><div style="max-height:min(48vh, 420px);overflow-y:auto;margin-bottom:16px;padding-right:4px" role="region" aria-label="Off-band validation explainer" data-testid="wizard-explainer-scroll"><section style="margin-bottom:16px"><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">BEAP is designed to validate messages safely by default. In standard mode, depackaging and validation run on this computer inside an isolated local container with fail-closed behavior and strict validation controls.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">This setup adds another layer for higher-risk environments: it deploys a small validation pod—built from the same code that runs on this computer—onto a Linux VPS you control. A small VPS with root access is enough.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">In high-assurance mode, email depackaging happens through the Edge Ingestor. The VPS receives the email content first, depackages it, validates it, and issues a cryptographic validation certificate. Only certified, validated content is then delivered to this computer.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Native BEAP capsules can still be received directly, depending on your security settings. For routes configured to require Edge Ingestor, the local app accepts only capsules with a valid Edge certificate. For routes that allow direct native BEAP, local container validation still runs normally.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">High-assurance mode reduces endpoint exposure further. Malformed attachments, zip bombs, complex MIME structures, and high-volume invalid traffic are handled by the VPS before they reach this machine.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Your computer still performs full local validation as a second check. The Edge certificate is a gate, not a replacement. If the certificate is missing where required, invalid, or local validation fails, the message is rejected.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">The Edge Ingestor also signs the validated content and its hashes. Any tampering between the VPS and this computer invalidates the certificate.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">Local AI analysis remains available to assess phishing, scam, and social-engineering risks before the user interacts with the message. In high-assurance mode, links and attachments should not be opened inside the host environment. Paid tiers can clone the message to a connected sandbox orchestrator, where links and attachments are opened off-band instead of on this computer.</p><p style="margin:0 0 10px;color:#cbd5e1">This mode is intended for users and organizations with higher assurance requirements. It does not mean standard BEAP validation is insecure; it adds an additional off-band isolation layer for cases where the stakes are higher.</p></section></div><footer data-testid="wizard-explainer-cta"><button type="button" style="padding:8px 14px;border-radius:6px;border:1px solid #6366f1;background:#4f46e5;color:#fff;cursor:pointer;font-size:13px;font-weight:600" data-testid="wizard-explainer-continue">Continue to deployment</button></footer></article>"`;

